Point is we’re still queer. Kids raised in “you’ll go to hell if you’re gay” are still queer, they’re just haunted by it because it’s who they are and they can’t change it. Trans kids grow into trans adults. We could all grow up with a lot less trauma if we had support earlier.

I went to Bible college. It was incredibly traumatic — both as a closeted queer person and as a disabled person. Like many other queer people I was in school with, we’re all still queer. We just refused to keep feeling guilty about it. Some of us even became queer Christians.

While we’re here the Christian Bible doesn’t even actually preach about homosexuality. The word wasn’t even added until 1946. King James had a gay lover. I’m also tired about the focus of every legislation being “what does the Bible say?” I w
 https://t.co/BWGyeXvVpz

No one deserves to go their whole life not knowing there are other people like them and thinking something is wrong with them. Queer kids deserve support, not to be told that they should be hidden from the world, or that they don’t exist.

But — queer kids are still going to be queer. They’re just not going to be receiving the support they need. Many already aren’t. I know growing up I didn’t have any education about this stuff. The longer you don’t know, the harder it can be when you finally do.

We’re still here. We’re still queer. But we have to work that much harder to advocate for ourselves & the next generation, and they know that. They know we’re exhausted. And they know that if they can hide us from the next generation they can undo so much of what we work for.

To help the next generation. These people supporting legislation like the Dont Say Gay bill want to break us down. They don’t want a generation of PRIDE parades, they want people who don’t have anywhere to turn for the questions they have. They want to undo all our advocacy.

This is kind of why I started writing about ace stuff in the first place — I didn’t want another person to go their whole life not knowing nothing is wrong with them for being ace. I know a lot of queer people who talk about their experiences for similar reasons — to help others.

These laws don’t benefit queer kids. They don’t benefit trans kids. They don’t benefit kids exploring. They don’t benefit adults trying to help them. They benefit the insecurities of people who don’t want the LGBTQIA+ community to exist. But we exist anyway.

Not being exposed to queer topics as a kid didn’t make me less queer. It made me feel like I had to fake something I didn’t have words for and caused a lot of stress and unnecessary trauma. All because adults around me were uncomfortable with the idea that queer people exist.

It’s okay to not want sex. It’s okay to want it. What’s not okay is pressuring your partner into it or telling them something is wrong with them or they can’t love you if they say no. Let people say no. Let people who don’t want sex be.

I did want to put out there that not being interested in sex, whether you’re ace or not, is fine and it’s important to discuss your needs and comfort levels about these things with your partner multiple times throughout your relationship as your needs change.

I didn’t want to quote tweet this because I didn’t want to directly give it attention, and because the comments are just… they’re a lot. And there’s a lot of pain there, and a lot of bashing aces. And we deal with that enough. Don’t need it on the timeline.

Sex can be an important component of a relationship, but if not having it is truly awful to you, I think it’s worth asking yourself why you feel that way and if the partnership would still be a good one for you if, for any reason, sex was removed completely from the equation.
these are fine. You can’t be sex positive without the right to say no for any reason. Ace, allo, whatever — sex positive thinking must include saying no.

There are also many other reasons why sex might stop being a part of a relationship. Obviously I wanted to point out how this perspective is one that harms aces interested in relationships but there are also many other reasons that sex might no longer be a part of the equation.

Like for a long time I thought I needed it because I didn’t hold myself or other things I could offer in high regard. Now I view it differently. it’s meaningful to me if I choose to have it, but it’s not a relationship requirement.

Not everyone wants sex and that’s OKAY. For others it’s an important part of the relationship. You need to be communicating your needs and expectations and respecting another persons right to say that isn’t for them. R*pe culture, purity culture and evangelicalism go hand in hand. But aces are still here. And deserve to feel like our bodies are ours, no matter our gender.
@booday Hi!

I’m not sure how to end this. This is just one perspective. But no matter your gender or sexuality, please know that your body is yours. And if you are demisexual there’s nothing wrong with that — regardless of your gender or how your present.
Demisexuals, graysexuals, asexuals — all exist across genders and across gender presentations. We do. Hi.

And I wish I could explain to properly to people who tell me it’s “just being a woman”— how I could explain that demisexual men exist, that gender is not a binary but rather a social construct, that many women LOVE sex — but it seems often to fall on ears that aren’t listening.

Learning not just about my gender but also about demisexuality existing and  no, not everyone is like that has been freeing actually as it tells me that my sexual attraction, orientation, and bodily autonomy matter. But I wish I’d believed that before I discovered my aceness.

I also internalized this to such a degree that when a boy I was dating in middle school asked if he could kiss me I didn’t understand why he had asked. And this internalized “you are only there for others” is something I’m still unlearning. I’m sure I’m not alone in that.

These ideas don’t empower people, but rather strip sexuality from us, making it no longer a matter of our own sexuality but instead our bodies something to be consumed. And it’s something I still see play out all the time in evangelicalism. And I hate it.

And beyond that, there’s not knowing what I didn’t know and how this reflects on not knowing to even ask anyone about what sexual attraction is. I grew up going to church camp, church every Sunday, “take care of your body for your future husband”.

I think it’s something that makes me very nervous about my book. Like… how do I explain to you that I know many allosexuals also don’t engage in casual sex? How do I explain that it’s not just a standard but rare sexual attraction, but standards are fine to have?

And I do. I like looking feminine. I love makeup. I also like not wearing it and I really dislike wearing dresses. But deep down I don’t think this stuff is gendered, really — the world at large just perceives it as such. Just like I’m seen as a woman; I know I am.

Granted, most people who dismiss demisexuality to me also dismiss that I am agender / non-binary — after all, why then dress in feminine clothes? Why bother with makeup? Surely I’m just a woman who is insecure in herself & following a trend?  “I think it’s pretty” isn’t enough. https://t.co/FKbHOJFwQ1

It’s… difficult and frustrating to say the least that the idea that an entire group of people aren’t supposed to enjoy sex is so pervasive that it leads people to dismiss an entire sexual orientation and the spectrum therein. Explored that a bit too: https://t.co/NXjcvnpfvW
(I wrote a thing about this idea a couple years ago. Because you don’t know what you aren’t seeing if you think you’re seeing it the same way as the people around you. https://t.co/pM8EyiIrrm )

And it’s very difficult to explain to someone that you spent most of your life thinking you saw a color but didn’t because no one told you that you didn’t see it the same way — they thought you saw it like they did. You don’t know to ask what you don’t know.

I think most everyone has standards for who they want to have sex with, whether conscious of it or not. Sexual orientation, however, is something innate, even if it changes with time. It’s a part of how you see and experience the world; a part of the colors you see.

The world sees me as a woman, not as an agender/NB person who likes dressing up because makeup is  fun and I like how I look in it. “I don’t have sexual attraction at all until a close bond is formed” is seen as having high standards for sex, not a sexual orientation.

The whole “isn’t that how everyone is?” is a thought I had before I knew more about it. I know now it’s not just “how everyone is”, or just “being a woman”. But I can understand where that misunderstanding comes from. Culturally, I’m not supposed to like sex.

There are so many reasons why “just move” is unhelpful. It’s like “we know you’re in a stack of needles, but just go over there, an expensive and long process that you don’t have money for because you aren’t paid a living wage, and hope there aren’t needles.”

Even if every queer person could and did leave Texas & Florida, queer people are still going to be born there. Families move with queer kids, who have no control over that. Or what if you can’t afford out of state college tuition but need your degree for a career?

Doctors often have long waiting lists, even for finding a primary care physician. So someone could wait for several months and then find out their doctor believes they are wrong and need fixed. Then you gotta start over because no healthcare is often better than bad healthcare.

A lot of jobs still aren’t remote, and many that were only did that temporarily. Jobs are tied into healthcare and many health insurance plans are terrible and have high copays and you never know who is in network. Plus you need to find someone who is LGBTQIA + friendly.

“Move out of Texas/Florida” is not a great response to anti-queer legislation. For starters, there are homophobic lawmakers all over this country. Second, the resources and money needed to transport one person are a LOT, and that’s before you factor in jobs/families/etc

Whatever works for you, use it! By all means use it. If it’s meds, I hope people in your life understand that. If it isn’t, I’m a little jealous because internalized ableism, but also I hope the people in your life understand. Whatever it is, I’m glad it works for you.

And I know a lot of other people who are in the same boat with their ADHD, who it is a serious impairment for, who do need access to medication.& I know lots of people who manage it without medication and have found other strategies that work better for them. We’re all different.

ADHD is a double edged sword. I love my fast brain, that I’m highly creative, that I’m easily excited and enthusiastic. I also can’t access those parts of myself when I’m literally paralyzed by executive dysfunction and it feels like all my thoughts are piling over each other.

It’s a lesson I have to keep re learning because I want deep down to not struggle with such basic things. Who doesn’t want to not struggle to just exist? But for me, that’s just not how my brain works. Meds don’t solve everything but they make life accessible for me.

For me, meds give me access to the amount of function to do things like exercise, take my vitamins, do my dishes, etc. I still have to do things like exercise and try to manage my time and put effort into everything, but without meds… I can’t try hard enough to do the BASICS.

Tried just exercising, which helps, but it’s not nearly enough. I’ve tried caffeine pills. Vitamins. Mushroom supplements. Amino acids. Alarms. Timers. Period breaks for movement. Sticky notes everywhere. Planners. SO MANY PLANNERS. And more. but none of those help without meds.

I also don’t think people realize that I don’t love taking them? I’m never sure when doctors will stop giving me access to them, they can flatten my emotions… but they give me my life back. And I have tried everything else I can afford to try. Like. Everything.

Functioning doesn’t just mean being able to do my job or get good grades. It also means emotional regulation, attention regulation, being able to plan one task after you finish another, being able to task switch, being able to stop doing something, and so much more.

And part of that functioning is not being stuck in rumination of “you suck / you’re lazy / why do you suck / no one loves you /etc”. And meds help me get out of that rumination, stop being stuck, and get to the parts of myself I do like. Because I’m functioning.

There are a lot of parts of my ADHD I love, but without help and medication I can’t access them. I can’t try hard enough to access those parts of my brain because everything gets paralyzed without help. I advocate so hard for meds because they are SO important for me to function.

It’s also important to treat and manage ADHD, even when not with stimulant medications, because it greatly effects emotional regulation and recovery from things like PTSD https://t.co/AkIrtHGRZ1

When you say stuff like this it blows up because it’s ignoring so much ableism we already have to deal with, as well as the consequences of that ableism, which can include but aren’t limited to what I talked about in this thread https://t.co/20xvJJKajH
You can also learn more about what ADHD actually is here: https://t.co/sAadJYGrnI

Brain differences are super interesting. If you want to learn about how these medications work and why they’re prescribed for ADHD, instead of tweeting out ableist uninformed takes on a disorder you don’t have, here’s this https://t.co/jDMTa7rCZK

This is because our brains don’t regulate dopamine & norepinephrine properly, or get it where it needs to be. ADHD meds help us get to a baseline. If you already are regulating these chemicals and you add stuff to make them go faster, it makes you go faster. See the difference?

Stimulant medications are strictly controlled and obtaining an ADHD diagnosis is a lengthy process, if you can obtain one at all. There are people who abuse these medications and people who sell them. If you don’t have ADHD, they’re like speed. If you have it, it’s not speed.

Also methamphetamines enter the blood brain barrier 5x faster than stimulant medications like adderall or vyvanse, which work differently than the stimulant medications Ritalin and concerta. Many people with ADHD also take nonstimulants or use other tools for management.

We have studied and found that ADHDers have a difference in brain structure in comparison to persons without ADHD. https://t.co/EPhEKCnGzF

Like… capitalism makes all disabilities and chronic illnesses worse, and ADHD should be renamed by people with ADHD. But the idea of “if you didn’t have to work in capitalism you wouldn’t need help for ADHD” is a slap in the face to both ADHDers and decades of neuroscience.

If this challenges you, good! Learn more about asexuality. I promise, there is a wealth of knowledge just waiting to challenge you and open your eyes to a whole new world of experiences.

And while sexual attraction may drive some in their pursuit of sexual pleasure, attraction and action are not one and the same. An ace individual’s libido does not cancel out their aceness, and neither does their sexual activity.

and may be something completely different than anything you’ve heard before. Asexuality and the spectrum of it houses a wide variety of experiences, people, and orientations. The one thing they all have in common is little to no sexual attraction.

These are all separate from each other and can be matched up in any number of ways.There are so many ways that an individual may experience and seek experiences that do not dilute or erase their asexuality. no matter who you’re talking to, their experience will be unique to them,

essentially you have three components: sexual attraction, a libido, and sexual activity, or action. The question is how they are experienced by the individual and where the individual finds themselves regarding the spectrum of sexual attraction, libido, and action.

sexuality concerning the asexual spectrum, this is one of the most important things to learn, and it is something that has to be learned over and over again, especially when we are taught our entire lives that if we do one thing it must mean another.

sexual attraction and action are not the same things. You may be sexually attracted to another person and never have sex with them. You may have no sexual attraction and have sex with another person for a variety of reasons. When we discuss unlearning expectations regarding
Which means you have a spectrum of actions, libido, and little to no sexual attraction. I tried to include some examples of the variety of ways that can play out here. https://t.co/mztot8JSVy

There are plenty of aces with high libido. Then there are many with no libido. And many with libido that fluctuates. The spectrum of asexuality being not about low libido is said because the spectrum is about sexual ATTRACTION, not action. And because it is a spectrum.

When I say that libido and sexual attraction are two different things and that the spectrum of asexuality isn’t about low libido, that isn’t to say that all aces have high libido. Instead, it’s to say that aces have different levels of libido, separate from sexual attraction. 🧵

Maybe it seems easier on the surface. And everyone’s experiences are different. But not experiencing sexual and/or romantic attraction doesn’t mean we have it easier, or that we don’t have romantic partnerships, or that we don’t experience heartbreak of all kinds.

Being ace doesn’t necessarily mean you don’t have romantic, sexual, or platonic relationships, and neither does being aro. Ace & aro  & aroace people can have all kinds of different relationships— from romantic to sexual to polyamorous to queerplatonic. Or we can have none!

not gonna lie I also have trouble doing this so I use an app called ‘mixed captions’ for captioning videos for things like Tiktok & Instagram videos. I also try to add image descriptions on Twitter but Twitter eats alt text a lot.
